<hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/683"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_683_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=76203e2149b4369effb0a5ead2b5548f&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="dr monica schraefel, Senior Lecturer in the School of Electronics and Computer Science, with the mSpace team:Daniel Alexander Smith, Alisdair Owens, Alistair Russel and Craig Harris " title="dr monica schraefel, Senior Lecturer in the School of Electronics and Computer Science, with the mSpace team:Daniel Alexander Smith, Alisdair Owens, Alistair Russel and Craig Harris  (Copyright: Steve Shrimpton)" border="0" width="120" height="82" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/683">ECS team launches new semantic web interface for smarter searches</a></h3><p>A new semantic web interface,mSpace, which will improve access to information and present search results in associated categories in one window, is launched this week from the School of Electronics and Computer Science. This new approach means that instead of users having to wade through long lists of search data to decide what is relevant, the interface will enable the machine to pull related sources into one usable view.</p><p></p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/681"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_681_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=24ac99ad72d6e552c3b3f21328b1a3d2&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="Chemist using the Smart Tea digital lab book to record an experiment" title="Chemist using the Smart Tea digital lab book to record an experiment" border="0" width="120" height="90" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/681">Chemistry of a cuppa: Helping to digitize laboratories of the future</a></h3><p>The brewing of tea formed a crucial component of a project which successfully took traditional paper laboratory books and moved them to digital formats. That knowledge and experience is now being put to use in a subsequent project by researchers from the School of Electronics and Computer Science who are aiming to apply similar techniques to Bioinformatics.</p></div><hr /><div class="frontNewsItem odd"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/679"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_679_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=8ecd113f4756a98236ae27c66b17ac8f&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="chiral nanostructures " title="chiral nanostructures " border="0" width="120" height="80" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/679">Nano surfaces could slash cost of solar energy</a></h3><p>Nanotechnologies which can artificially change the optical properties of materials to allow light to be trapped in solar cells could greatly reduce the cost of solar energy. Research being carried out by Dr Darren Bagnall of the School's Nanoscale Systems Integration group is focusing on nanopatterning as the way to design effective solar panels.</p><p></p></div><div class="frontNewsItem even"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/678"><img src="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840im_/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/image.php?id=news_678_img&amp;maxw=120&amp;maxh=120&amp;corners=10&amp;edge=1&amp;checksum=3665cb8083b411f7e4e4b4fc2e8a948d&amp;fn=fn.png" alt="" title="" border="0" width="120" height="120" class="thumbnail" /></a><h3><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/678">New name for world-leading ECS research group</a></h3><p>Nanoscale Systems Integration (NSI) is the new title for one of the School of Electronics and Computer Science's eight world-leading research groups. According to Head of Group, Professor Greg Parker, NSI (previously known as Microelectronics) has undergone considerable change and development over the years and the new title reflects new research directions and interests.</p></div><p class="clearBoth"><a href="http://ia360911.us.archive.org:9090/wayback/20050224085840/http://www.ecs.soton.ac.uk/news/">More News</a></p><br style="clear: both;" />
